</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) has a high incidence of recurrence following therapy. Therefore, secondary surveillance (scheduled follow-up imaging after treatment) is an important part of disease management. The recent approval in the United States for use of a microbubble-based contrast agent for US liver imaging promotes the increased use of contrast-enhanced US (CEUS) in patients with HCC. Although the criteria for the diagnosis of HCC at CEUS are well described, there is a paucity of published literature describing the role of CEUS in ablative therapy and secondary surveillance. In the setting of ablative therapy, CEUS can have vital roles, including patient selection, intraprocedural guidance, and immediate postprocedural assessment. Although CEUS is not widely used, the authors found that it can be used to accurately detect residual or recurrent tumor, characterize the geographic pattern of recurrence (intrazonal, extrazonal, segmental, or remote), and assess for tumor in vein. In addition, similar to primary surveillance, secondary surveillance includes assessment of the entire liver for evaluation of new nodules. Arterial phase hyperenhancement is the reference standard characteristic of disease recurrence at secondary surveillance with CEUS.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div><div role="paragraph">See discussion on this article by <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2019190049">Rodgers</a>.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180205">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180205">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig1a.jpeg" height="1261" width="1523" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Classic LI-RADS category 5 HCC in a 59-year-old man with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a 3.5-cm heterogeneous echogenic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS scan obtained 30 seconds after contrast material injection shows arterial phase hyperenhancement (APHE) of the nodule (arrow). <b>(c)</b> CEUS scan obtained 4 minutes after the injection shows definite weak washout (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig1b.jpeg" height="1260" width="1625" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Classic LI-RADS category 5 HCC in a 59-year-old man with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a 3.5-cm heterogeneous echogenic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS scan obtained 30 seconds after contrast material injection shows arterial phase hyperenhancement (APHE) of the nodule (arrow). <b>(c)</b> CEUS scan obtained 4 minutes after the injection shows definite weak washout (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig1c.jpeg" height="1219" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Classic LI-RADS category 5 HCC in a 59-year-old man with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a 3.5-cm heterogeneous echogenic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS scan obtained 30 seconds after contrast material injection shows arterial phase hyperenhancement (APHE) of the nodule (arrow). <b>(c)</b> CEUS scan obtained 4 minutes after the injection shows definite weak washout (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig2.jpeg" height="3885" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Authors’ CEUS technique for liver nodule assessment. The essential images to acquire include a cine loop–audiovisual <i>(AVI)</i> image file, beginning with the appearance of the first microbubble until just after the arterial phase enhancement peak; a static image obtained 1 minute after contrast material injection; and static images obtained every 60 seconds, up to 300 seconds. For all intents and purposes, 0.2 mL of perflutren microspheres is equivalent to approximately 1.6–2.4 mL of sulfur hexafluoride. <i>IV</i> = intravenous.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig3.jpeg" height="2069" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Diagram outlines the BCLC HCC staging system. <i>ECOG</i> = Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group Performance Status, SBRT = stereotactic body radiation therapy. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from reference 10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig4.jpeg" height="2310" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Flowchart outlines the timing of CEUS in relation to the ablative therapy procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig5a.jpeg" height="1706" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Successful MWA of HCC in a 46-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment gray-scale US image shows a hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Pretreatment CEUS image obtained 10 seconds after contrast material administration shows APHE (arrow). There was late weak washout (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after MWA shows heterogeneous echogenicity (arrow) within the treatment site; this finding is not dissimilar to that seen on the pretreatment gray-scale image <b>(a)</b>. <b>(d)</b> CEUS image obtained 9 months after MWA and 20 seconds after contrast material injection shows the treatment site (arrow) to be completely avascular, consistent with a successful ablation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig5b.jpeg" height="1706" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Successful MWA of HCC in a 46-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment gray-scale US image shows a hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Pretreatment CEUS image obtained 10 seconds after contrast material administration shows APHE (arrow). There was late weak washout (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after MWA shows heterogeneous echogenicity (arrow) within the treatment site; this finding is not dissimilar to that seen on the pretreatment gray-scale image <b>(a)</b>. <b>(d)</b> CEUS image obtained 9 months after MWA and 20 seconds after contrast material injection shows the treatment site (arrow) to be completely avascular, consistent with a successful ablation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig5c.jpeg" height="1702" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Successful MWA of HCC in a 46-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment gray-scale US image shows a hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Pretreatment CEUS image obtained 10 seconds after contrast material administration shows APHE (arrow). There was late weak washout (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after MWA shows heterogeneous echogenicity (arrow) within the treatment site; this finding is not dissimilar to that seen on the pretreatment gray-scale image <b>(a)</b>. <b>(d)</b> CEUS image obtained 9 months after MWA and 20 seconds after contrast material injection shows the treatment site (arrow) to be completely avascular, consistent with a successful ablation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig5d.jpeg" height="1702" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Successful MWA of HCC in a 46-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment gray-scale US image shows a hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Pretreatment CEUS image obtained 10 seconds after contrast material administration shows APHE (arrow). There was late weak washout (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after MWA shows heterogeneous echogenicity (arrow) within the treatment site; this finding is not dissimilar to that seen on the pretreatment gray-scale image <b>(a)</b>. <b>(d)</b> CEUS image obtained 9 months after MWA and 20 seconds after contrast material injection shows the treatment site (arrow) to be completely avascular, consistent with a successful ablation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig6a.jpeg" height="1218" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Imaging findings demonstrate the value of CEUS performed immediately after MWA in a 74-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Preprocedural CEUS image shows a nodule (arrows) with APHE 30 seconds after contrast agent injection. Late weak washout was seen at 3 minutes (not shown), consistent with classic HCC. The patient went on to undergo MWA of this nodule. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 10 minutes after the ablation and 15 seconds after the injection shows a residual hyperenhancing nodule (arrow) adjacent to the ablation zone. The ablation zone is superficial to the residual zone of hyperenhancement, suggesting inadvertent withdrawal of the MWA probe during treatment. Repeat ablation was performed immediately. <b>(c)</b> Second CEUS image, obtained 10 minutes after the second ablation and 30 seconds after the injection, shows no residual areas of hyperenhancement (arrow). This finding was confirmed at follow-up MRI and CEUS performed during secondary surveillance (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig6b.jpeg" height="1218" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Imaging findings demonstrate the value of CEUS performed immediately after MWA in a 74-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Preprocedural CEUS image shows a nodule (arrows) with APHE 30 seconds after contrast agent injection. Late weak washout was seen at 3 minutes (not shown), consistent with classic HCC. The patient went on to undergo MWA of this nodule. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 10 minutes after the ablation and 15 seconds after the injection shows a residual hyperenhancing nodule (arrow) adjacent to the ablation zone. The ablation zone is superficial to the residual zone of hyperenhancement, suggesting inadvertent withdrawal of the MWA probe during treatment. Repeat ablation was performed immediately. <b>(c)</b> Second CEUS image, obtained 10 minutes after the second ablation and 30 seconds after the injection, shows no residual areas of hyperenhancement (arrow). This finding was confirmed at follow-up MRI and CEUS performed during secondary surveillance (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig6c.jpeg" height="1219" width="1571" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Imaging findings demonstrate the value of CEUS performed immediately after MWA in a 74-year-old man with ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Preprocedural CEUS image shows a nodule (arrows) with APHE 30 seconds after contrast agent injection. Late weak washout was seen at 3 minutes (not shown), consistent with classic HCC. The patient went on to undergo MWA of this nodule. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 10 minutes after the ablation and 15 seconds after the injection shows a residual hyperenhancing nodule (arrow) adjacent to the ablation zone. The ablation zone is superficial to the residual zone of hyperenhancement, suggesting inadvertent withdrawal of the MWA probe during treatment. Repeat ablation was performed immediately. <b>(c)</b> Second CEUS image, obtained 10 minutes after the second ablation and 30 seconds after the injection, shows no residual areas of hyperenhancement (arrow). This finding was confirmed at follow-up MRI and CEUS performed during secondary surveillance (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig7a.jpeg" height="1216" width="1565" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Imaging findings show the strength of CEUS in the assessment and accurate diagnosis of a hypovascular nodule (LI-RADS category 4 biopsy-proven HCC) in a 38-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a predominantly hypoechoic nodule (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection shows transient arterial phase hypoenhancement of the nodule; this is not a classic finding of HCC. Owing to its hypovascularity, this nodule was not well seen at CT (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images show the nodule (arrow) isoenhancing relative to the liver parenchyma 30 seconds after the injection <b>(c)</b> and with weak washout at 1.5 minutes <b>(d)</b>. Subsequent marked washout was seen during the late phase (not shown). PEI was the selected treatment for this patient, as the lesion was in close proximity to the colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig7b.jpeg" height="1216" width="1566" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Imaging findings show the strength of CEUS in the assessment and accurate diagnosis of a hypovascular nodule (LI-RADS category 4 biopsy-proven HCC) in a 38-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a predominantly hypoechoic nodule (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection shows transient arterial phase hypoenhancement of the nodule; this is not a classic finding of HCC. Owing to its hypovascularity, this nodule was not well seen at CT (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images show the nodule (arrow) isoenhancing relative to the liver parenchyma 30 seconds after the injection <b>(c)</b> and with weak washout at 1.5 minutes <b>(d)</b>. Subsequent marked washout was seen during the late phase (not shown). PEI was the selected treatment for this patient, as the lesion was in close proximity to the colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig7c.jpeg" height="1196" width="1540" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Imaging findings show the strength of CEUS in the assessment and accurate diagnosis of a hypovascular nodule (LI-RADS category 4 biopsy-proven HCC) in a 38-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a predominantly hypoechoic nodule (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection shows transient arterial phase hypoenhancement of the nodule; this is not a classic finding of HCC. Owing to its hypovascularity, this nodule was not well seen at CT (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images show the nodule (arrow) isoenhancing relative to the liver parenchyma 30 seconds after the injection <b>(c)</b> and with weak washout at 1.5 minutes <b>(d)</b>. Subsequent marked washout was seen during the late phase (not shown). PEI was the selected treatment for this patient, as the lesion was in close proximity to the colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig7d.jpeg" height="1198" width="1591" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Imaging findings show the strength of CEUS in the assessment and accurate diagnosis of a hypovascular nodule (LI-RADS category 4 biopsy-proven HCC) in a 38-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a predominantly hypoechoic nodule (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection shows transient arterial phase hypoenhancement of the nodule; this is not a classic finding of HCC. Owing to its hypovascularity, this nodule was not well seen at CT (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images show the nodule (arrow) isoenhancing relative to the liver parenchyma 30 seconds after the injection <b>(c)</b> and with weak washout at 1.5 minutes <b>(d)</b>. Subsequent marked washout was seen during the late phase (not shown). PEI was the selected treatment for this patient, as the lesion was in close proximity to the colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig8a.jpeg" height="1215" width="1566" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. US-guided MWA in a 63-year-old man with treated hepatitis C virus and ethanol alcohol– and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image enables excellent visualization of the MWA probe tip (arrow) in a hypoechoic nodule. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the treatment-related development of a large gas cloud (arrow) in the ablation zone, with an associated hyperechoic artifact distally, after successful US-guided MWA. The gas cloud is causing significant obscuration of the treatment site. This finding typically takes 5–15 minutes to resolve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig8b.jpeg" height="1215" width="1566" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. US-guided MWA in a 63-year-old man with treated hepatitis C virus and ethanol alcohol– and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image enables excellent visualization of the MWA probe tip (arrow) in a hypoechoic nodule. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the treatment-related development of a large gas cloud (arrow) in the ablation zone, with an associated hyperechoic artifact distally, after successful US-guided MWA. The gas cloud is causing significant obscuration of the treatment site. This finding typically takes 5–15 minutes to resolve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig9a.jpeg" height="1519" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Reactive hyperemia in two patients. <b>(a)</b> CEUS image obtained immediately after MWA in a 26-year-old woman with HCC shows a uniform smooth rim of APHE (arrow) around the treatment zone. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 4 months after TACE in a 67-year-old man with hepatitis C virus– and ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis shows an avascular treatment site, with a relatively smooth peripheral rim of APHE (arrow). Reactive hyperemia is frequently seen on immediate postprocedural CEUS images. During secondary surveillance, it is an uncommon but normal finding. The hyperemic rim generally is significantly larger than the original nodule, enabling the presumptive differentiation of reactive hyperemia versus residual tumor. In addition, reactive hyperemia typically shows sustained enhancement without washout (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig9b.jpeg" height="1519" width="1962" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Reactive hyperemia in two patients. <b>(a)</b> CEUS image obtained immediately after MWA in a 26-year-old woman with HCC shows a uniform smooth rim of APHE (arrow) around the treatment zone. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 4 months after TACE in a 67-year-old man with hepatitis C virus– and ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis shows an avascular treatment site, with a relatively smooth peripheral rim of APHE (arrow). Reactive hyperemia is frequently seen on immediate postprocedural CEUS images. During secondary surveillance, it is an uncommon but normal finding. The hyperemic rim generally is significantly larger than the original nodule, enabling the presumptive differentiation of reactive hyperemia versus residual tumor. In addition, reactive hyperemia typically shows sustained enhancement without washout (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig10.jpeg" height="2417" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Diagram illustrates the authors’ local secondary surveillance imaging schedule after therapy for HCC. The left column shows the secondary imaging surveillance schedule for patients with HCC-negative findings (−, solid arrows), with expedited MRI or CEUS performed as a result of any HCC-positive finding (+, dashed arrows) discovered during secondary surveillance (middle). The right column illustrates the further management required after HCC-negative or HCC-positive findings are discovered at expedited MRI or CEUS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig11.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Chart illustrates geographic HCC recurrence (orange) patterns. Intrazonal recurrence occurs within a treatment site. Extrazonal recurrence refers to recurrent tumor that is juxtaposed to, but outside of, the treatment site. Segmental recurrence occurs within the same segment as the previously treated lesion, but with normal intervening liver tissue. Remote recurrence refers to a tumor that appears in a liver segment that is different from the segment of the previously treated neoplasm and thus typically represents de novo HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig12a.jpeg" height="1296" width="1671" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Intrazonal recurrence after PEI in a 63-year-old woman with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after PEI shows a typical heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a nodular region of APHE (arrows) within the treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 3 minutes shows marked washout (arrows). This patient underwent repeat ablative therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig12b.jpeg" height="1296" width="1671" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Intrazonal recurrence after PEI in a 63-year-old woman with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after PEI shows a typical heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a nodular region of APHE (arrows) within the treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 3 minutes shows marked washout (arrows). This patient underwent repeat ablative therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig12c.jpeg" height="1296" width="1671" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Intrazonal recurrence after PEI in a 63-year-old woman with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after PEI shows a typical heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a nodular region of APHE (arrows) within the treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 3 minutes shows marked washout (arrows). This patient underwent repeat ablative therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig13a.jpeg" height="1621" width="2095" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Intrazonal recurrence after RFA in a 76-year-old man with primary biliary cirrhosis and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. Faint enhancement in the treatment site was seen at MRI (not shown) 1 month after treatment. Expedited CEUS was requested for further assessment. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 2 months after treatment shows a heterogeneous 6.7-cm treatment site (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular APHE (arrow) in the treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows weak late washout (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig13b.jpeg" height="1621" width="1254" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Intrazonal recurrence after RFA in a 76-year-old man with primary biliary cirrhosis and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. Faint enhancement in the treatment site was seen at MRI (not shown) 1 month after treatment. Expedited CEUS was requested for further assessment. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 2 months after treatment shows a heterogeneous 6.7-cm treatment site (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular APHE (arrow) in the treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows weak late washout (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig13c.jpeg" height="1712" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Intrazonal recurrence after RFA in a 76-year-old man with primary biliary cirrhosis and nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. Faint enhancement in the treatment site was seen at MRI (not shown) 1 month after treatment. Expedited CEUS was requested for further assessment. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 2 months after treatment shows a heterogeneous 6.7-cm treatment site (arrow) in liver segment V. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular APHE (arrow) in the treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows weak late washout (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig14a.jpeg" height="1219" width="1572" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Extrazonal recurrence after RFA in a 49-year-old woman with alcoholic cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after treatment shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrowhead) and a vague nodule (arrows) juxtaposed to the treatment site border. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular APHE (arrows), corresponding to the vague nodule seen in <b>a,</b> adjacent to the avascular treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows definite weak washout (arrows) of the recurrent tumor adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig14b.jpeg" height="1218" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Extrazonal recurrence after RFA in a 49-year-old woman with alcoholic cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after treatment shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrowhead) and a vague nodule (arrows) juxtaposed to the treatment site border. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular APHE (arrows), corresponding to the vague nodule seen in <b>a,</b> adjacent to the avascular treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows definite weak washout (arrows) of the recurrent tumor adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig14c.jpeg" height="1220" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Extrazonal recurrence after RFA in a 49-year-old woman with alcoholic cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after treatment shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrowhead) and a vague nodule (arrows) juxtaposed to the treatment site border. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular APHE (arrows), corresponding to the vague nodule seen in <b>a,</b> adjacent to the avascular treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows definite weak washout (arrows) of the recurrent tumor adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig15a.jpeg" height="1287" width="1659" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. The value of CEUS in imaging-guided therapy for HCC recurrence after multiple prior treatments in a 62-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows three adjacent hyperechoic nodule-like regions (arrows). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows APHE in one of the nodules (arrow), consistent with disease recurrence. The two other nodules are completely avascular, consistent with successful treatment sites. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 75 seconds shows weak washout of the enhancing nodule (arrow), while the treatment sites remain avascular. This case highlights the capability of CEUS for differentiating viable tumor from prior successful treatment sites and thus enabling US-guided ablative therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig15b.jpeg" height="1289" width="1483" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. The value of CEUS in imaging-guided therapy for HCC recurrence after multiple prior treatments in a 62-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows three adjacent hyperechoic nodule-like regions (arrows). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows APHE in one of the nodules (arrow), consistent with disease recurrence. The two other nodules are completely avascular, consistent with successful treatment sites. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 75 seconds shows weak washout of the enhancing nodule (arrow), while the treatment sites remain avascular. This case highlights the capability of CEUS for differentiating viable tumor from prior successful treatment sites and thus enabling US-guided ablative therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig15c.jpeg" height="1291" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. The value of CEUS in imaging-guided therapy for HCC recurrence after multiple prior treatments in a 62-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows three adjacent hyperechoic nodule-like regions (arrows). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows APHE in one of the nodules (arrow), consistent with disease recurrence. The two other nodules are completely avascular, consistent with successful treatment sites. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 75 seconds shows weak washout of the enhancing nodule (arrow), while the treatment sites remain avascular. This case highlights the capability of CEUS for differentiating viable tumor from prior successful treatment sites and thus enabling US-guided ablative therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig16a.jpeg" height="1385" width="1786" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Simultaneous segmental and intrazonal recurrence after RFA in an 80-year-old woman with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after RFA shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular foci of APHE in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to but separate from the treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images obtained 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> and 6 minutes <b>(d)</b> after the injection show that the APHE foci in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead) are isoenhancing relative to the adjacent parenchyma and demonstrate late weak washout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig16b.jpeg" height="1586" width="1227" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Simultaneous segmental and intrazonal recurrence after RFA in an 80-year-old woman with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after RFA shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular foci of APHE in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to but separate from the treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images obtained 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> and 6 minutes <b>(d)</b> after the injection show that the APHE foci in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead) are isoenhancing relative to the adjacent parenchyma and demonstrate late weak washout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig16c.jpeg" height="1586" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Simultaneous segmental and intrazonal recurrence after RFA in an 80-year-old woman with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after RFA shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular foci of APHE in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to but separate from the treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images obtained 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> and 6 minutes <b>(d)</b> after the injection show that the APHE foci in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead) are isoenhancing relative to the adjacent parenchyma and demonstrate late weak washout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig16d.jpeg" height="1586" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span>. Simultaneous segmental and intrazonal recurrence after RFA in an 80-year-old woman with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 9 months after RFA shows a heterogeneous treatment site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows nodular foci of APHE in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to but separate from the treatment site (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> CEUS images obtained 2 minutes <b>(c)</b> and 6 minutes <b>(d)</b> after the injection show that the APHE foci in the treatment site (arrow) and adjacent to the treatment site (arrowhead) are isoenhancing relative to the adjacent parenchyma and demonstrate late weak washout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig17a.jpeg" height="1448" width="1868" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Malignant portal vein tumor thrombus in a 56-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 5 months after RFA shows a hyperechoic focus (arrow) in the right portal vein, with no Doppler flow (not shown), consistent with a thrombus. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows APHE of the right portal vein thrombus (white arrow). The hepatic arteries (black arrows) are bright and contain microbubbles; the remainder of the portal vein is dark. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 3 minutes shows weak washout (arrow), consistent with a malignant tumor thrombus, which is surrounded by microbubbles in the residual patent lumen of the portal vein (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig17b.jpeg" height="1447" width="1553" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Malignant portal vein tumor thrombus in a 56-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 5 months after RFA shows a hyperechoic focus (arrow) in the right portal vein, with no Doppler flow (not shown), consistent with a thrombus. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows APHE of the right portal vein thrombus (white arrow). The hepatic arteries (black arrows) are bright and contain microbubbles; the remainder of the portal vein is dark. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 3 minutes shows weak washout (arrow), consistent with a malignant tumor thrombus, which is surrounded by microbubbles in the residual patent lumen of the portal vein (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig17c.jpeg" height="1450" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Malignant portal vein tumor thrombus in a 56-year-old man with hepatitis B virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 5 months after RFA shows a hyperechoic focus (arrow) in the right portal vein, with no Doppler flow (not shown), consistent with a thrombus. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 15 seconds after contrast agent injection shows APHE of the right portal vein thrombus (white arrow). The hepatic arteries (black arrows) are bright and contain microbubbles; the remainder of the portal vein is dark. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 3 minutes shows weak washout (arrow), consistent with a malignant tumor thrombus, which is surrounded by microbubbles in the residual patent lumen of the portal vein (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig18a.jpeg" height="1220" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Bland portal vein thrombosis in a 52-year-old man with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale/color Doppler US image obtained 9 months after RFA shows subtle hyperechogenicity (arrow) within the entire imaged main portal vein, with no Doppler flow in this region, consistent with a thrombus. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast material injection shows avascularity of the thrombus (arrow), consistent with a bland rather than malignant thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig18b.jpeg" height="1218" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Bland portal vein thrombosis in a 52-year-old man with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale/color Doppler US image obtained 9 months after RFA shows subtle hyperechogenicity (arrow) within the entire imaged main portal vein, with no Doppler flow in this region, consistent with a thrombus. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast material injection shows avascularity of the thrombus (arrow), consistent with a bland rather than malignant thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig19a.jpeg" height="1597" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Postablation hepatic abscess in a 63-year-old man with nonalcoholic fatty liver disease–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image 2 months after RFA shows a large heterogeneous treatment site. There are several superficial internal regions of hyperechogenicity with dirty posterior acoustic shadowing, consistent with air (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection shows complete avascularity at the site of the treated tumor. A small superficial focus of air remains visible (arrow). The mass was confirmed to be a successful treatment site complicated by abscess.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig19b.jpeg" height="1595" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Postablation hepatic abscess in a 63-year-old man with nonalcoholic fatty liver disease–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image 2 months after RFA shows a large heterogeneous treatment site. There are several superficial internal regions of hyperechogenicity with dirty posterior acoustic shadowing, consistent with air (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection shows complete avascularity at the site of the treated tumor. A small superficial focus of air remains visible (arrow). The mass was confirmed to be a successful treatment site complicated by abscess.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig20a.jpeg" height="1081" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Subcutaneous tumor seeding along the percutaneous probe tract in a 63-year-old man with hepatitis C virus– and ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows two distinct subcutaneous nodular foci with APHE (arrows) along the tract of a previous RFA treatment. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows washout in the enhancing subcutaneous nodular foci (arrows), consistent with tumor seeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig20b.jpeg" height="1081" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Subcutaneous tumor seeding along the percutaneous probe tract in a 63-year-old man with hepatitis C virus– and ethanol alcohol–related cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows two distinct subcutaneous nodular foci with APHE (arrows) along the tract of a previous RFA treatment. <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes shows washout in the enhancing subcutaneous nodular foci (arrows), consistent with tumor seeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig21.jpeg" height="619" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Successful hepatic wedge resection in a 65-year-old man with hepatitis C virus–related cirrhosis. CEUS image obtained 5 years after the surgery shows a large void (arrow) without vascularity in liver segments II and III, corresponding to the site of prior wedge resection. There was no evidence of washout on images obtained in later phases (not shown). The findings are consistent with successful hepatic wedge resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig22a.jpeg" height="1740" width="1665" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Intrazonal recurrence of HCC 4 months after hepatic wedge resection in a 50-year-old man with hepatitis B–related cirrhosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Gray-scale US <b>(a)</b> and CEUS <b>(b)</b> images show classic HCC in liver segments V and VI. The tumor appears as a hypoechoic nodule (arrow in <b>a</b>) abutting the liver capsule at gray-scale US and with APHE (arrow in <b>b</b>) on the CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection. Histopathologic analysis revealed poorly differentiated HCC. The patient underwent hepatic wedge resection. <b>(c–e)</b> Posttreatment US revealed intrazonal recurrence, seen as a heterogeneous postsurgical bed (arrow in <b>c</b>) on a gray-scale image 4 months after the wedge resection, nodular APHE (arrow in <b>d</b>) in the postsurgical bed on a CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection, and weak washout (arrow in <b>e</b>) on a CEUS image at 3 minutes. Recurrent tumor was confirmed at subsequent, urgently performed MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig22b.jpeg" height="1740" width="1666" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Intrazonal recurrence of HCC 4 months after hepatic wedge resection in a 50-year-old man with hepatitis B–related cirrhosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Gray-scale US <b>(a)</b> and CEUS <b>(b)</b> images show classic HCC in liver segments V and VI. The tumor appears as a hypoechoic nodule (arrow in <b>a</b>) abutting the liver capsule at gray-scale US and with APHE (arrow in <b>b</b>) on the CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection. Histopathologic analysis revealed poorly differentiated HCC. The patient underwent hepatic wedge resection. <b>(c–e)</b> Posttreatment US revealed intrazonal recurrence, seen as a heterogeneous postsurgical bed (arrow in <b>c</b>) on a gray-scale image 4 months after the wedge resection, nodular APHE (arrow in <b>d</b>) in the postsurgical bed on a CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection, and weak washout (arrow in <b>e</b>) on a CEUS image at 3 minutes. Recurrent tumor was confirmed at subsequent, urgently performed MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig22c.jpeg" height="1296" width="1669" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Intrazonal recurrence of HCC 4 months after hepatic wedge resection in a 50-year-old man with hepatitis B–related cirrhosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Gray-scale US <b>(a)</b> and CEUS <b>(b)</b> images show classic HCC in liver segments V and VI. The tumor appears as a hypoechoic nodule (arrow in <b>a</b>) abutting the liver capsule at gray-scale US and with APHE (arrow in <b>b</b>) on the CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection. Histopathologic analysis revealed poorly differentiated HCC. The patient underwent hepatic wedge resection. <b>(c–e)</b> Posttreatment US revealed intrazonal recurrence, seen as a heterogeneous postsurgical bed (arrow in <b>c</b>) on a gray-scale image 4 months after the wedge resection, nodular APHE (arrow in <b>d</b>) in the postsurgical bed on a CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection, and weak washout (arrow in <b>e</b>) on a CEUS image at 3 minutes. Recurrent tumor was confirmed at subsequent, urgently performed MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig22d.jpeg" height="1289" width="1669" aria-labelledby="fig22d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22d</span>. Intrazonal recurrence of HCC 4 months after hepatic wedge resection in a 50-year-old man with hepatitis B–related cirrhosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Gray-scale US <b>(a)</b> and CEUS <b>(b)</b> images show classic HCC in liver segments V and VI. The tumor appears as a hypoechoic nodule (arrow in <b>a</b>) abutting the liver capsule at gray-scale US and with APHE (arrow in <b>b</b>) on the CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection. Histopathologic analysis revealed poorly differentiated HCC. The patient underwent hepatic wedge resection. <b>(c–e)</b> Posttreatment US revealed intrazonal recurrence, seen as a heterogeneous postsurgical bed (arrow in <b>c</b>) on a gray-scale image 4 months after the wedge resection, nodular APHE (arrow in <b>d</b>) in the postsurgical bed on a CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection, and weak washout (arrow in <b>e</b>) on a CEUS image at 3 minutes. Recurrent tumor was confirmed at subsequent, urgently performed MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig22d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig22e.jpeg" height="1295" width="1667" aria-labelledby="fig22e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22e</span>. Intrazonal recurrence of HCC 4 months after hepatic wedge resection in a 50-year-old man with hepatitis B–related cirrhosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Gray-scale US <b>(a)</b> and CEUS <b>(b)</b> images show classic HCC in liver segments V and VI. The tumor appears as a hypoechoic nodule (arrow in <b>a</b>) abutting the liver capsule at gray-scale US and with APHE (arrow in <b>b</b>) on the CEUS image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent injection. Histopathologic analysis revealed poorly differentiated HCC. The patient underwent hepatic wedge resection. <b>(c–e)</b> Posttreatment US revealed intrazonal recurrence, seen as a heterogeneous postsurgical bed (arrow in <b>c</b>) on a gray-scale image 4 months after the wedge resection, nodular APHE (arrow in <b>d</b>) in the postsurgical bed on a CEUS image 30 seconds after the injection, and weak washout (arrow in <b>e</b>) on a CEUS image at 3 minutes. Recurrent tumor was confirmed at subsequent, urgently performed MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig22e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig23a.jpeg" height="1228" width="1585" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Nonlinear artifact resulting in pseudoenhancement that mimicked tumor recurrence in a 77-year-old woman with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after MWA shows a heterogeneous treatment site in liver segment VI, with central hyperechogenicity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a completely avascular treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 45 seconds, during the early portal venous phase, shows progressive enhancement (arrow) within the treatment site. The enhancement corresponds to the hyperechogenicity seen in <b>a</b> and is discontinuous with the margin of the treatment zone. <b>(d)</b> On the CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes, the degree of enhancement seen in <b>c</b> is unchanged.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig23b.jpeg" height="1228" width="1556" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Nonlinear artifact resulting in pseudoenhancement that mimicked tumor recurrence in a 77-year-old woman with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after MWA shows a heterogeneous treatment site in liver segment VI, with central hyperechogenicity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a completely avascular treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 45 seconds, during the early portal venous phase, shows progressive enhancement (arrow) within the treatment site. The enhancement corresponds to the hyperechogenicity seen in <b>a</b> and is discontinuous with the margin of the treatment zone. <b>(d)</b> On the CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes, the degree of enhancement seen in <b>c</b> is unchanged.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig23c.jpeg" height="1228" width="1556" aria-labelledby="fig23c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23c</span>. Nonlinear artifact resulting in pseudoenhancement that mimicked tumor recurrence in a 77-year-old woman with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after MWA shows a heterogeneous treatment site in liver segment VI, with central hyperechogenicity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a completely avascular treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 45 seconds, during the early portal venous phase, shows progressive enhancement (arrow) within the treatment site. The enhancement corresponds to the hyperechogenicity seen in <b>a</b> and is discontinuous with the margin of the treatment zone. <b>(d)</b> On the CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes, the degree of enhancement seen in <b>c</b> is unchanged.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig23c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180205/asset/images/large/rg.2019180205.fig23d.jpeg" height="1228" width="1585" aria-labelledby="fig23d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23d</span>. Nonlinear artifact resulting in pseudoenhancement that mimicked tumor recurrence in a 77-year-old woman with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image obtained 1 month after MWA shows a heterogeneous treatment site in liver segment VI, with central hyperechogenicity (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CEUS image obtained 30 seconds after contrast agent injection shows a completely avascular treatment site. <b>(c)</b> CEUS image obtained at 45 seconds, during the early portal venous phase, shows progressive enhancement (arrow) within the treatment site. The enhancement corresponds to the hyperechogenicity seen in <b>a</b> and is discontinuous with the margin of the treatment zone. <b>(d)</b> On the CEUS image obtained at 4 minutes, the degree of enhancement seen in <b>c</b> is unchanged.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180205&amp;id=fig23d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Ferlay J, Soerjomataram I, Dikshit R, et al. Cancer incidence and mortality worldwide: sources, methods and major patterns in GLOBOCAN 2012. <em>Int J Cancer</em> 2015;136(5):E359–E386.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/ijc.29210">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25220842/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Cancer+incidence+and+mortality+worldwide%3A+sources%2C+methods+and+major+patterns+in+GLOBOCAN+2012&amp;author=J+Ferlay&amp;author=I+Soerjomataram&amp;author=R+Dikshit&amp;publication_year=2015&amp;journal=Int+J+Cancer&amp;pages=E359-E386&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fijc.29210&amp;pmid=25220842">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Cronin KA, Lake AJ, Scot